    <div class="prose-shopify mb-12">
      <h2>Marketing priorities for beauty brands</h2>
      <p>Beauty brands break when email treats every subscriber the same. The pressure point is replenishment timing, bundles, subscriptions, shades, and routine education. A disciplined email marketing program must coordinate consent, lifecycle timing, product context, and margin-aware measurement — not blast more coupons.</p>
      <p>Priority plays: Replenishment by product usage; Routine education sequences; Shade matching follow-up; Subscription skip/churn prevention. Document suppressions for recent purchasers, wholesale accounts, and active support cases before scaling sends.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first for beauty brands because lifecycle editorial beats newsletter volume: welcome by signup source, replenishment matched to consumption, winback with VIP exclusions.</p>
      <p>Klaviyo remains the benchmark when beauty brands need predictive segmentation and native Shopify event depth at scale. Omnisend wins when email + SMS must go live before month end.</p>
      <p>Track Replenishment conversion rate, Subscription retention at 90 days, Bundle attach rate from email, Unsubscribe rate on education vs promo weekly. Email ROI appears when incremental repeat purchase rises while unsubscribe and complaint rates stay flat.</p>
      <p>Buying cycle reality: 30–90 day replenishment windows; strong subscription potential; shade/variant complexity. Email cadence must respect that rhythm — not the marketing calendar alone.</p>
      <p>Implementation: audit consent sources in week one, launch welcome segmented by source in week two, add cart or post-purchase in week three, measure repeat purchase movement in week four.</p>
      <p>Peak season for beauty brands requires pausing non-essential flows, protecting VIP segments, and aligning merchandising with inbox promises — governance matters more than new app installs.</p>
      <p>Deliverability note: beauty brands with aggressive promos need authentication, frequency caps, and sunset policies — complaint spikes often trace to offer mismatch, not weak templates.</p>
      <p>Pair capture tools (Privy, Justuno) only when list growth is the leak; pair Postscript when SMS recovery justifies cost. Avoid three senders without a collision calendar.</p>
      <p>Read comparisons and use-case playbooks on this site for head-to-head tradeoffs and execution detail specific to replenishment timing, bundles, subscriptions, shades, and routine education.</p>
      <h3>Where beauty operators leak revenue</h3>
      <p>Replenishment misfires when timing ignores SKU consumption math — hair mask every six weeks is not shampoo every four. Subscription skip spikes when preview content fails to excite before skip deadline. Shade mismatch drives returns when post-purchase follow-up skips undertone education.</p>
      <p>Salon wholesale and DTC in one list without suppression destroys both channels. Shopify email marketing apps cannot fix channel conflict — but hard account separation prevents consumer promos reaching professional buyers.</p>
      <p>Reading path for beauty: Sequenzy first for {segment.emailPriorities[0]}; layer Yotpo when {segment.metrics[2]} justifies proof timing; Klaviyo when shade and subscription predictive segments need weekly ownership. {segment.buyingCycle} governs every replenishment timer — not the content calendar.</p>
    </div>
