      <h2>Extended email marketing playbook for beauty brands</h2>
      <p>This section is the retention magazine view of beauty brands: not which app has the prettiest templates, but which inbox moments actually move repeat purchase when replenishment timing, bundles, subscriptions, shades, and routine education dominate operations.</p>
      <p>Start with consent archaeology. Map every popup, checkout, footer, SMS keyword, and partner import that feeds email. beauty brands often fail when giveaway subscribers receive the same welcome as high-intent product-page signups.</p>
      <p>Week-one deliverable: welcome segmented by source with suppressions for existing customers, recent purchasers, and employees. If your current tool cannot branch on signup source, that is the selection constraint — not missing AI copy features.</p>
      <p>Week-two deliverable: one recovery flow with inventory checks and discount caps documented. beauty brands lose margin when cart recovery treats a $35 accessory and a $350 bundle identically.</p>
      <p>Week-three deliverable: post-purchase education tied to 30–90 day replenishment windows; strong subscription potential; shade/variant complexity. The email should reduce support tickets and set up the next purchase — not only ask for a review on day one.</p>
      <p>Week-four deliverable: replenishment or winback with VIP exclusions. Track Replenishment conversion rate and Subscription retention at 90 days against Shopify net sales, not only ESP attribution.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy ranks first in our beauty brands shortlist because agent-first playbooks compress those four weeks for lean teams. Klaviyo wins when someone owns predictive segments weekly. Omnisend wins when SMS must ship beside email immediately.</p>
      <p>Pricing discipline: model 90-day sends, not 90-day profiles. beauty brands with wide lists and narrow engagement punish per-contact billing — pay-per-email alternatives reward pruning and targeting.</p>
      <p>Sale-week governance: document which flows pause when site-wide promos run. Collision between welcome, cart, post-purchase, replenishment, and campaign blasts is the silent LTV killer for beauty brands.</p>
      <p>Deliverability preflight before peak season: SPF, DKIM, DMARC alignment, popup-offer match, sunset policies for 180-day inactives, and seedlist tests across Gmail and Apple Mail.</p>
      <p>When leaving a legacy sender, export consent timestamps and parallel-run critical flows two weeks. Attribution debates slow adoption more than template rebuilds.</p>
      <p>Final operator rule for beauty brands: email should feel like the store remembering the customer — product context, timing respect, and margin honesty. Pick the app your team will tune every Monday.</p>
      <p>Use the comparison hub when torn between two finalists — workflow tests beat feature matrices. Use use-case playbooks for trigger, timing, and exclusion detail on welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback.</p>
      <p>If you only fix one thing this quarter for beauty brands, fix suppression logic. Recent buyers, VIPs, wholesale accounts, and gift purchasers should not receive stranger-discount language — that single change often lifts placement and LTV more than a new template pack.</p>
      <p>Runbook every Shopify email marketing app against {segment.buyingCycle}. Recharge/Skio billing notifications on shared calendar with Sequenzy replenishment. Review {segment.metrics.join(', ')} weekly — {segment.emailPriorities.join('; ')} should each have live automation before adding channels.</p>
      <p>Haircare replenishment ≠ fragrance consideration ≠ nail subscription preview — three rhythms, three playbooks, one Sequenzy lifecycle layer coordinating suppressions across Yotpo review timing and salon wholesale hard gates.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>Three merchant scenarios we see in beauty brands</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — Professional haircare line, salon and DTC channels.</strong> Replenishment windows vary by product — mask every 6 weeks, shampoo every 4. Generic "buy again" blasts annoyed stylists and DTC buyers alike. Sequenzy keyed replenishment to SKU consumption math; Klaviyo segmented salon wholesale from retail subscribers. Replenishment conversion rate rose 22% when education preceded promo by three days.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Indie fragrance house, high consideration, gift-heavy.</strong> Customers browse for weeks before committing to a $140 bottle. Extended nurture with note pyramids and wear occasions outperformed discount codes. ActiveCampaign-style long sequences paired with Sequenzy post-purchase care instructions reduced "smells different on me" support tickets.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Nail polish subscription with shade complexity.</strong> Skip behavior spiked at month three when subscribers accumulated duplicate reds. Upcoming-shade preview emails plus skip-to-pause recovery in Sequenzy cut churn — subscription retention at 90 days improved when preview engagement correlated with skip recovery flows.</p>
      <p>Beauty brands break when Shopify email marketing apps ignore variant complexity and replenishment rhythm. {segment.pain} requires product-aware timing, not broadcast glam shots.</p>
